editorialSummary.text: Indie bands & more make some noise at this sprawling venue on the western fringe of Hell's Kitchen.

originalText.text: If you get a chance to see one of your favorite bands here, I highly suggest you do it. It's such a great intimate venue. I saw the run the jewels 10th anniversary here and it couldn't have been a better experience. There are no bad places to stand here. If you're the kind of person that wants some place to sit, however, you will need to get a VIP spot. But I feel sitting down during a concert in this venue is doing the disservice to the experience.

originalText.text: The stage is very far away, the sound is all bouncy and kind of terrible, it's in the middle of nowhere.. not much to do that is close by, like if you wanted to get a drink after the show or a late dinner.. you would be forced to walk up (and up, and up) a very steep incline just to get back to civilization. So yeah, not my favorite place to see a band-although LCD Soundsystem still killed it.

originalText.text: oversold tinashe like crazy. i couldn’t see the stage at any point of the concert. getting out was a security hazard and people were panicking, having asthma attacks because we were herded out through one door and with no security around to tell use any information. it took ~25+ min just to leave the building because they only opened one door for the whole sold out venue. there was a big chance of a crowd crush as people got more anxious and claustrophobic and pushing.

originalText.text: Went to see Polyphia and I gotta say the experience was a great one. Security was great as they made precautions to keep people safe. During the performances there were many crowd surfers and security made sure to catch them at the front to make sure they didn’t hurt themselves and were handing out water to keep people hydrated. Drinks were a bit on the expensive side as expected. But overall I recommend it if you have a concert there. 10/10 experience would definitely recommend.
